Review: Feeling overwhelmingly grateful for William Friedkin, Lance Reddick, and anyone and everyone else who dedicates their life to the movies. This film has meaningful and interesting things to say, but on an even more profound level it’s about when People Talk In A Room. The movies, man. The movies.

I feel like this is the thing where there’s a movie about like a helicopter pilot and it’s compelling and people like it but then a helicopter pilot watches it and is like “why would they make any decisions like that, they should have been trained to do other things”, etc etc. Watching this protagonist double and triple and quadruple down on her mistakes was mostly just repetitive and frustrating. Kids rock though, solidarity forever.

Movie: It's a Bird, It's a Plane, It's Superman!
Review: An absolutely beautiful object. Everybody gets the pitch of the thing. Great aesthetic, great songs. Superman as Coop from Wet Hot. Mobsters with thick accents. Should be accepted as the canonical piece of superhero cinema it so clearly is.

Felt "ooh, this is the good stuff" as soon as Keith David's name showed up in the awesome opening credits and that feeling held basically through the whole runtime. Jeffrey Wright is one of the most compelling actors alive. I can't wait to see what Cord Jefferson does next.
with Jared Harris as Goatee Smoker
Forrest Gump is a good genre

I imagine there must come a time where any rich and powerful man who loves a sports team realizes that there is nothing they can do to *make* said team win a championship. They might have creative or financial freedoms beyond our wildest dreams, but they can't make this happen. Nobody can. Some even go to the point where they buy the team. This, of course, is not enough. You can't will it into being.Mike Myers' Maple Leafs may…

Maybe the most heartbreaking thing here - and that really is saying something - is that Kevin really *is* the lucky one. Those who have to withstand the losses around them and live with the pains and traumas of existence are the ones who are still here. No 2023 movie moment made me cry harder than the final-frame family photo. Living well is the best revenge, as the saying goes. That may be cheesy, but existing on this planet is…

Movie: The Buried Secret of M. Night Shyamalan
Review: One of M. Night's better acting performances IMO
Quite bad - and even so, Myers probably has at least 20 unbelievably funny bits and gags. Kind of a shame he disappeared.

Increasingly in awe of Shyamalan's chops as a filmmaker. Of all the movies of his I've seen thus far, Old (which rules) is the only one that I think actually qualifies as a horror movie. Perhaps thriller is the right descriptor, but that doesn't quite feel right either. His movies just have their own emotional timbre, a Sirk-meets-Spielberg dance of faith and loss and hope. There's nothing quite like them. He feels like someone who will be hailed once again…
Ben Platt engaging in self-parody does little to mitigate his intensely unlikable screen persona
